<h2>Frequently Asked Questions — LG Washer CE Error</h2>

<h3>What does the CE code mean on my LG washer?</h3>
<p>CE means the motor is drawing too much electrical current and the control shut down to protect itself. It can be as simple as an overloaded or jammed drum, or as involved as a motor or control-board fault — it doesn't always mean a dead motor.</p>

<h3>Can I fix an LG washer CE error myself?</h3>
<p>Sometimes. Unplug it, take out part of the load if the drum is overstuffed, and turn the drum by hand to feel for anything jammed between the drum and the tub. Power-cycle and restart; if it runs freely and CE clears, you're set. If it returns, the motor or control needs testing.</p>

<h3>How much does it cost to fix an LG washer CE error?</h3>
<p>If it's an overload or a stuck object, it's a quick service call with the $65 diagnostic waived when we do a repair. If the motor or control board is at fault, that work runs $300–420 depending on the part. We test the motor circuit before quoting so you're not paying for guesses. We're licensed with the Bureau of Household Goods and Services (#49573).</p>

<h3>Why does my LG washer trip CE during the wash or spin?</h3>
<p>That's when the motor works hardest, so an extra-heavy load, a jam, or a weakening motor pushes current past the limit and the control cuts out. A short in the motor windings does the same thing under load. We measure the motor's current draw to separate an overload from a real fault.</p>

<h3>Is it safe to keep using my LG washer with a CE error?</h3>
<p>No — repeatedly restarting a washer that's drawing too much current risks the motor and the control board. Clear any obstruction and lighten the load once; if CE comes back, leave it off and get the motor circuit checked.</p>

